{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cb7f6f02-f1fb-4b48-9e2e-cb17523d77f6","content":"These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**Error 1 — `&&` with `dynamic` operand**\n\nThe `&&` operator is sugar for: `operator true(left) ? left : left & right`. It requires three operators on the left operand's type: `operator true`, `operator false`, **and** `operator &`.\n\nIn C# 14 and earlier, when `right` was `dynamic`, the entire `&&` was deferred to the runtime binder. **C# 15 now requires all three operators to be statically resolvable** on the left operand's compile-time type.\n\n`IFilter` defines `operator true`/`operator false` but **not** `operator &`, so the compiler rejects `left && right`.\n\n**Fix:** Add `operator &` to `IFilter`:\n\n```csharp\ninterface IFilter\n{\n    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;\n    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;\n    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;  // add this\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Error 2 — `ref readonly` return lambda (`CS0518`)**\n\nCS0518 means *\"Predefined type 'System.X.Y' is not defined or imported.\"* C# 15 changed how `ref readonly` return types are encoded on synthesized delegate types, requiring a new well-known attribute type (for encoding the `readonly` ref-return semantics in metadata).\n\nIf your compiler is C# 15 but your project still **targets an older TFM** (e.g., `net10.0`), the required type won't exist in the referenced runtime assemblies.\n\n**Fix:** Ensure your project actually targets .NET 11:\n\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\nOr, if you can't retarget yet, avoid delegate synthesis by declaring an explicit delegate type:\n\n```csharp\ndelegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();\n\nstatic void M()\n{\n    RefReadOnlyFunc fn = () => ref value;\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"33a6b2a7-8ac9-4586-822b-707abb724d49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases:\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to how the `&&` operator interacts with `dynamic` operands.\n\nThe `&&` operator is a short-circuit operator that relies on `operator true`, `operator false`, and `operator &`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to resolve these operators at compile time for the static operand's type.\n\n\nThe problem is that `IFilter` defines `operator true` and `operator false` as static operators with default implementations on the interface itself. In earlier versions, the compiler could work with these interface-level static operators when one operand was `dynamic`, but C# 15 appears to have stricter requirements about how it resolves these operators in mixed static/dynamic scenarios.\n\nThe real issue is that `&&` desugars to `operator true(left) ? left : left & right`, and when the right operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to handle the interaction between the static operators on the interface type and the dynamic binding—which seems to be causing a conflict in the newer version. `IFilter` has `operator true` and `operator false` defined, but lacks `operator &`. The dynamic right operand used to force runtime resolution of the whole expression, but C# 15 appears to have changed this so the compiler now requires static resolution of `operator true`/`operator false` on the left operand even when the right side is `dynamic`. I'm trying to pinpoint exactly what changed in the recent .NET versions around how `dynamic` interacts with short-circuit operators.\n\nThe second issue involves a `ref readonly` lambda that's triggering a CS0518 error about a missing predefined type, which suggests the runtime needs a specific delegate type to support `ref readonly` return types on lambdas. For lambdas with `ref readonly` returns, C# needs a compatible delegate type since the standard `Func<T>` delegates don't support `ref` returns. The CS0518 error suggests the compiler is looking for a runtime type needed to synthesize the delegate, possibly something in the compiler's delegate inference infrastructure that's missing from the target runtime.\n\nLooking at both errors more carefully, the first one with dynamic and `&&` is likely a breaking change where the compiler now requires the `operator &` to be statically resolvable on the left operand's type, and since `IFilter` has `operator true`, this constraint is now being enforced differently.\n\nFor the second error with `ref readonly` lambdas, the compiler needs certain well-known types like `ScopedRefAttribute` to synthesize the delegate type, and even though the user upgraded to .NET 11, the project might not be properly referencing the updated runtime libraries that contain these types.\n\nBut actually, thinking about this more carefully—the user said this code *used* to compile before upgrading to .NET 11 and C# 15, so this is a breaking change. The `&&` with dynamic probably worked before because everything was dynamically bound, but now the compiler is trying to statically resolve parts of it, which is a known type of breaking change in newer versions.\n\nFor the `ref readonly` lambda case, the CS0518 error specifically means a predefined type is missing, which suggests C# 15 introduced new requirements for handling `ref readonly` return lambdas—either a new attribute, a new type, or a change in how the syntax is parsed. I'm not even certain `ref readonly` return lambdas were valid syntax before C# 13 or later, so I need to focus on what's actually changed rather than speculating. For Error 2, the issue might be that C# 15 now supports `ref readonly` return types on lambdas, but the compiler infrastructure to synthesize the appropriate delegate types with `in` modifiers isn't fully available—it could be missing a required attribute like `IsReadOnlyAttribute` or needs specific runtime support that isn't present in the current framework version. The syntax itself might be recognized, but the underlying type infrastructure to make it work hasn't been properly set up yet. might be a breaking change in C# 15 for how `ref readonly` returns are handled on lambdas, potentially requiring a new runtime type that wasn't needed before. The CS0518 error suggests the compiler is looking for a specific predefined type—possibly something in `System.Runtime.CompilerServices` related to `ref readonly` semantics—that either doesn't exist in the current BCL or wasn't required in earlier versions. a newer language feature that requires a runtime type not available in the target framework. So the user likely needs to either upgrade their TFM to .NET 11 or use a traditional delegate type instead of a lambda with `ref readonly` return. ized delegate type that was added in .NET 11. So the issue is that C# 15 now requires this attribute for `ref readonly` return types on lambdas, but it's not available in older target frameworks.\n\nFor the `&&` operator issue, C# 15 changed how it handles `dynamic` operands. The compiler now requires the left operand's type to statically define all three operators—`operator true`, `operator false`, and `operator &`—at compile time. Previously it would fall back to dynamic resolution when the right side was `dynamic`, but now it's stricter. Since `IFilter` only has the first two operators, the compilation fails. I'd need to add the missing `operator &` implementation to fix it.\n\nFor the `ref readonly` lambda issue, the problem is likely a mismatch between the C# 15 compiler and the target framework. If the project is still targeting something like `net10.0` while using the C# 15 compiler, it won't have access to the required runtime types. Updating to `net11.0` and ensuring the latest runtime packages are installed should resolve it.","outputTokens":4669,"requestId":"A45F:F3EF4:239ADAF:27573DB:6A03D98D"},"id":"e6b74028-f7d1-47f